    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1963-08-27T07:05:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1963-08-27T07:05:00-05:00" n="300"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d300">
                <head>300. Telegram From the Commander, Military Assistance Command, Vietnam
                        (<persName corresp="#p_HGPD1" type="from">Harkins</persName>) to the
                    Chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff(<persName corresp="#p_TGMD1" type="to"
                        >Taylor</persName>)<note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d300fn1">Source:
                        National Defense University, <persName corresp="#p_TGMD1">Taylor</persName>
                        Papers, T-172-69. Top Secret; Eyes Only. Repeated to Honolulu for
                        Felt.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <hi rend="italic">
                            <placeName>Saigon</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                                when="1963-08-27T20:05:00+08:00">August 27, 1963, 8:05 p.m.</date>
                        </hi>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>MAC 1540. Ref A. <gloss target="#t_JCS1">JCS</gloss> 3354-63.<note n="2"
                        xml:id="d300fn2">
                        <ref target="#d295">Document 295</ref>.</note> B. <gloss
                        target="#t_CINCPAC1">CINCPAC</gloss> 260302Z.<note n="3" xml:id="d300fn3">In
                        this telegram, August 26, <gloss target="#t_CINCPAC1">CINCPAC</gloss> stated
                        that Embassy and <gloss target="#t_COMUSMACV1">COMUSMACV</gloss> plans for
                        security and evacuation in the event of a coup were sound. <gloss
                            target="#t_CINCPAC1">CINCPAC</gloss> also believed that <persName
                            corresp="#p_HGPD1">Harkins</persName> had enough U.S. troops to evacuate
                        the estimated 4,600 American noncombatants in Vietnam. (<persName
                            corresp="#p_KJE1">Kennedy</persName> Library, National Security Files,
                        Vietnam Country Series, 8/24/63-8/31/63, Defense Cables)</note> Following
                    observation keyed to paras of ref A:</p>
                <p>1. US personnel, military and civilian are in no more immediate danger than
                    usual. However, recognize full well that in atmosphere which exists here this
                    situation could change momentarily. Situation is being closely monitored
                    continuously. Arrangements for security and evacuation well covered in existing
                    plans which support and are compatible with Embassy <gloss target="#t_EE1">E
                        &amp; E</gloss> plan. Am in direct liaison Embassy <gloss target="#t_EE1">E
                        &amp; E</gloss> officer on details. Published plans all based on assumption
                    that friendly local government will be in control. Possibility that this
                    assumption may not be valid has stimulated our thoughts along alternative
                    lines.</p>
                <p>Ref B indicates <gloss target="#t_CINCPAC1">CINCPAC</gloss>’s thoughts along this
                    line and action he has taken and is prepared to take in such an eventuality. We
                    are in detailed development and review of alternative courses of security and
                    emergency evacuation actions based on degree of loss of control by friendly
                    government. Cataloging of location of some 5000 US noncombatants in <gloss
                        target="#t_RVN1">RVN</gloss> in good shape, various notification nets appear
                    adequate and procedures checking out okay.</p>
                <p>Concur in <gloss target="#t_SECDEF1">SecDef</gloss> observation on use of
                    commercial air as primary evacuation mode. For alternative actions utilizes in
                    country and other immediately available govt evacuation transportation assets as
                    primary mode. [<hi rend="italic">sic</hi>]</p>
                <pb facs="0682" n="656" xml:id="pg_656"/>
                <p>2. In context of State 243 to Saigon<note n="4" xml:id="d300fn4">
                        <ref target="#d281">Document 281</ref>.</note> “direct support” interpreted
                    here as indicating that US diplomatic recognition will be forth coming promptly
                    and that US economic and military assistance to <gloss target="#t_RVN1"
                        >RVN</gloss> will continue as at present, even under most extreme
                    contingency of military coup in which not only Nhus but also <persName
                        corresp="#p_DIEM1">Diem</persName> is removed from scene.</p>
                <p>Specifically unless I receive other instructions I interpret “direct support” of
                    military as covering the following: <list>
                        <label>a.</label>
                        <item>Full military backing, military counsel and advice.</item>
                        <label>b.</label>
                        <item>Use of US communications and unarmed aircraft for troop transport,
                            supply, recce and command liaison.</item>
                        <label>c.</label>
                        <item>Denial of further funds, equipment, advice, communication and aircraft
                            to opposing military and paramilitary forces, and in particular, Col
                                <persName corresp="#p_TLQTT1">Tung</persName>’s units. <gloss
                                target="#t_CAS1">CAS</gloss> must of course also deny.</item>
                    </list>
                </p>
                <p>Feasibility of foregoing direct support measures in event pressure on armed
                    intervention from forces loyal to Palace depends in large part on how play
                    develops. Category of support covered in pare a above feasible under all
                    conditions, though effectiveness can be reduced should key <gloss
                        target="#t_MACV1">MACV</gloss> staff be restricted in freedom of movement’
                    Believe however, we have enough good people to carry on despite some
                    interruptions.</p>
                <p>As to pare b above, a hostile <gloss target="#t_VNAF1">VNAF</gloss> could
                    [garble] deny use of Tan Son Nhut and Bien Hoa. We will have to make tough
                    decisions as between further concentration of aircraft <gloss target="#t_VN1"
                        >VN</gloss>-USA-Bien Hoa complex which is pertinent to <gloss
                        target="#t_EE1">E and E</gloss> planning and dispersion suggested by maximum
                    support of coup. Present disposition of <gloss target="#t_USAF1"
                        >USAF</gloss>/USA/<gloss target="#t_USMC1">USMC</gloss> aircraft outside
                    Saigon area insures that we can provide considerable but not optimum assistance
                    to forces converging on capital. Deployment of forces estimated to side with
                    military takeover is reasonable assurance that major part of communication net
                    would be preserved.</p>
                <p>My best judgment as to reliability and alignment of senior military leaders is as
                    follows: <list>
                        <label>a.</label>
                        <item>Composition of group which would coalesce to plan and execute a
                            military takeover: <list>
                                <label>(1).</label>
                                <item>Gen Big Minh, Advisor to Pres <list>
                                        <item>Gen <persName corresp="#p_DON1">Don</persName>
                                        </item>
                                        <item>Gen Le, former JG of <gloss target="#t_CG1"
                                            >CG</gloss>, now deputy to <persName corresp="#p_DON1"
                                                >Don</persName>
                                        </item>
                                        <item>Gen Little Minh, IG, <gloss target="#t_ARVN1"
                                                >ARVN</gloss>
                                        </item>
                                        <item>Gen <persName corresp="#p_KHIEM1">Khiem</persName>,
                                            C/S, <gloss target="#t_JGS1">JGS</gloss>
                                        </item>
                                        <item>Gen <persName corresp="#p_KHANH1">Khanh</persName>, II
                                            Corps</item>
                                        <item>Gen Tri, I Corps</item>
                                        <item>Gen <persName corresp="#p_LVKBG1">Le Van
                                                Kim</persName>, currently deputy to <persName
                                                corresp="#p_DON1">Don</persName>
                                        </item>
                                        <item>Gen Chien, currently deputy to <persName
                                                corresp="#p_DON1">Don</persName>
                                        </item>
                                        <item>Col Vien, <gloss target="#t_CO1">CO</gloss> ADH
                                            Brigade</item>
                                    </list>
                                </item>
                                <pb facs="0683" n="657" xml:id="pg_657"/>
                                <label>(2).</label>
                                <item>Loyalty of all runs to <persName corresp="#p_DIEM1"
                                        >Diem</persName> not <persName corresp="#p_NHU1"
                                        >Nhu</persName>. Estimate that all, except <persName
                                        corresp="#p_DON1">Don</persName> and <hi rend="italic"
                                        >Le</hi>, convinced that both <persName corresp="#p_NHU1"
                                        >Nhu</persName> and <persName corresp="#p_DIEM1"
                                        >Diem</persName> must now go. bon and Le would probably
                                    accept retention of <persName corresp="#p_DIEM1">Diem</persName>
                                    as nominal head of state.</item>
                                <label>(3).</label>
                                <item>All are firmly pro-US with possible exception of Tri,. given
                                    his violent nationalism.</item>
                                <label>(4).</label>
                                <item>The only general to whom others would subordinate themselves
                                    is Big Minh.</item>
                                <label>(5).</label>
                                <item>Those most qualified and also in positions to take lead in
                                    planning are <persName corresp="#p_KHANH1">Khanh</persName>,
                                        <persName corresp="#p_KHIEM1">Khiem</persName>, Tri,
                                        <persName corresp="#p_KIM1">Kim</persName>, and Little Minh.
                                        <persName corresp="#p_DON1">Don</persName> is, of course,
                                    completely boxed in.</item>
                            </list>
                        </item>
                        <label>b.</label>
                        <item>Those who will stick with status quo, opposing takeover: <list>
                                <label>(1).</label>
                                <item>Gen <persName corresp="#p_DINH1">Dinh</persName>, III Corps <list>
                                        <item>Gen Cao, IV Corps</item>
                                        <item>Col <hi rend="italic">Tung</hi>, <gloss
                                                target="#t_CMDR1">Cmdr</gloss> Special Forces</item>
                                        <item>Col Hien, Co <gloss target="#t_VNAF1">VNAF</gloss>
                                        </item>
                                    </list>
                                </item>
                                <label>(2).</label>
                                <item>Estimate <persName corresp="#p_DINH1">Dinh</persName> and Cao
                                    would eventually attempt switch but too late. <persName
                                        corresp="#p_TLQTT1">Tung</persName> would go down swinging.
                                    Hien not likely to rally any significant portion of <gloss
                                        target="#t_VNAF1">VNAF</gloss>. No loyalty ties among any of
                                    four.</item>
                            </list>
                        </item>
                        <label>c.</label>
                        <item>The opportunists, who likely be aloof from planning but ready to jump
                            quickly: <list>
                                <item>Gen <persName corresp="#p_TTOBG1">Oai</persName>, <gloss
                                        target="#t_RVNAF1">RVNAF</gloss>
                                    <gloss target="#t_PSYWAR1">psywar</gloss> chief</item>
                                <item>Gen <persName corresp="#p_LA1">La</persName>, <gloss
                                        target="#t_CG1">CG</gloss> Capital Mil Dist</item>
                                <item>Capt Quyen, Cmdr, VNH</item>
                                <item>Col Khang, <gloss target="#t_CMDR1">Cmdr</gloss>
                                    <gloss target="#t_VNMC1">VNMC</gloss>
                                </item>
                            </list>
                        </item>
                    </list>
                </p>
                <p>4. Consensus here is that Vice President <persName corresp="#p_THO1"
                        >Tho</persName> is best candidate as man who all might rally behind as
                    Presidential successor.</p>
                <p>Will continue to maintain close liaison with Amb. <persName corresp="#p_LHCJ1"
                        >Lodge</persName>. Keeping him informed of what I am doing and will file
                    personal reports to <gloss target="#t_JCS1">JCS</gloss> and <gloss
                        target="#t_CINCPAC1">CINCPAC</gloss> as matters of significance
                    [garble—occur?].</p>
            </div>
